Marcellus Community Schools
August 1 at 11:04 AM ·

Just a reminder to vote on August 4. The district's non-homestead renewal is on the ballot. This millage represents an estimated $1.67 million for the district. That's a significant portion of the district's operating budget, so it is essential that Marcellus residents vote!
The non-homestead millage does not affect homeowners who use their homes as primary residences. Polls will be open from 7 a.m.-8 p.m. or registered voters can vote by absentee ballot.
Thank you!

Marcellus athletes, let's get back at it!

Click on the link below to understand the protocols for the workouts. The check in point will be at the middle gate by the weight room.

These workouts are for students (girls and boys) entering 9th through 12th grade next year. We will offer a morning and afternoon session to try and accommodate all athletes. The workouts will be designed for conditioning and body weight training. July will be designated for sport specific training and times will be determined by coaches.

We will offer MS and youth workouts in July.

post_text:
The Marcellus Athletic Department will be starting the process of creating a historical stat leader board for all sports in their major stat categories.

To ensure we have as accurate data as possible, we will need the help of former coaches, players and community members.

What we are asking at this time is to start searching in your archives for any material that would be helpful to us in completing this project. As we start to fill in the information we already have, we will then start asking for data to fill in the gaps.

If you have any questions or input please email stats@marcellusathletics.org

Marcellus is now offering club baseball and softball for this spring. Teams are open to any 7th and 8th grade students. The season will start March 23rd and the last game is May 23rd. Game schedule is listed below. Cost will be $50, which will cover a portion of the umpire fees and supplies. Please make checks payable to Marcellus Community Schools. Practices will be right after school until spring break and then a new schedule will be developed. Registration will be through Final Forms. If your son/daughter has played a sport this year, they are already in the system and just need to sign up for the spring sport. If this is the first season they will be playing, you will need to create an account.

Wednesday 4/22 Home vs. Cassopolis
Saturday 4/25 Home vs. Gobles
Wednesday 4/29 @ Lawton,
Saturday 5/2 Location TBD
Wednesday 5/6 Location TBD
Saturday 5/9 Home vs. Fennville/Cassopolis, 10:00
Wednesday 5/13 Home vs. Decatur
Saturday 5/16 @ Decatur
Wednesday 5/20 Home vs. Eau Claire
Saturday 5/23 @ Saugatuck, 10:00

If any businesses would like to sponsor games, we have 4 available spots (digital logo) for $100 each for the remainder of the year.

post_text:
The varsity wrestling team opened up league competition last night vs. White Pigeon and Centreville. They came away with a split, defeating Centreville and losing to White Pigeon.

Senior Blake Colley kept his undefeated season alive as he went 2-0 on the night. Also going 2-0 were Trevor Wilson, Nolan Robinson and Estevan Rodriguez. Going 1-0 was Chadlee Nestle.

Travis Marsh, Wyatt Maggert, Josh Mann and Dyllon Gebbink finished 1-1 on the night.

They will be competing in the Homer Tournament this weekend.

post_text:
Congratulations to the girls cross country team for once again qualifying for the MHSSA State Championship Meet. This past Saturday they took 3rd place at regionals to get the automatic qualifier. Valerie Vidal led the way finishing in 12th place and earning a medal. Other runners include; Ellie Tone, Romy Friconneau, Carolina Mauri, Mackenzie Bishop, Caylee Bishop and Savannah Lowery.

The girls will travel to Michigan International Speedway this Saturday to compete in the state championship.

The boys finished in 10th place and did not have any individual qualifiers.

This is a top notch facility we can all be proud of.

post_text:
We were saddened to hear of the passing of Corky Emrick this morning. Corky was professional, kind, caring and respectful whenever he came to cover Marcellus Athletics. He was excellent at covering and featuring local high school teams and athletes.

With very heavy hearts, the Marcellus Wildcats send our thoughts and prayers to the family and to the Sturgis Journal family.
